# Skills Lifecycle: RFP Response Drafter
# A skill that searches a document library, synthesizes institutional knowledge, and cites its sources.

[var: SITE = https://contoso.sharepoint.com/sites/demo/]
[var: ARCHIVE = ${SITE}Proposal%20Archive/]
[var: LIST = ${SITE}Lists/RFP%20Questions/]
[category: Skills]

[section: setup]

[navigate: ${SITE}]

[open-chat]

[new-chat]

[prompt: Create a document library called "Proposal Archive" if it doesn't already exist.]

[wait]

[assert: ${ARCHIVE}]

[navigate: ${ARCHIVE}]

Uploading the five past proposal documents.

[upload-library: tools/scripts/15-skills-rfp-response/assets/Zava Cloud Migration Proposal - Contoso 2024.docx]
[upload-library: tools/scripts/15-skills-rfp-response/assets/Zava Data Analytics Platform - Fabrikam 2024.docx]
[upload-library: tools/scripts/15-skills-rfp-response/assets/Zava Enterprise Support Services - Woodgrove 2024.docx]
[upload-library: tools/scripts/15-skills-rfp-response/assets/Zava Security and Compliance Overview - Northwind 2025.docx]
[upload-library: tools/scripts/15-skills-rfp-response/assets/Zava Professional Services and Training - Adatum 2025.docx]

[navigate: ${SITE}]

[new-chat]

[prompt: Delete the list called "RFP Questions" if it exists.]

[wait]

[sleep: 3s]

[new-chat]

[prompt: Create a new SharePoint list called "RFP Questions" with these columns: Title (single line of text, the question label — built-in Title column), Full Question (Multiple lines of text), Category (Choice: Technical, Security, Support, Pricing, Compliance, General), Priority (Choice: Must Answer, Nice to Have), Status (Choice: Open, Drafted, Reviewed, Submitted), Draft Response (Multiple lines of text), Sources Used (Multiple lines of text), Confidence (Single line of text).]

[wait]

[sleep: 5s]

[assert: ${LIST}]

[navigate: ${LIST}]

[new-chat]

[prompt: Add these 5 items to the RFP Questions list: 1. Title: "Cloud Migration Approach" | Full Question: "Describe your methodology for migrating enterprise workloads to Azure, including typical timelines, risk mitigation strategies, and references from similar engagements." | Category: Technical | Priority: Must Answer | Status: Open. 2. Title: "Data Security Standards" | Full Question: "Detail your security certifications, data encryption standards, and approach to zero-trust architecture. Include your incident response procedures and most recent third-party audit results." | Category: Security | Priority: Must Answer | Status: Open. 3. Title: "Support Model & SLAs" | Full Question: "What support tiers do you offer? Provide SLA response times, escalation procedures, and customer satisfaction metrics for your enterprise support program." | Category: Support | Priority: Must Answer | Status: Open. 4. Title: "Training & Change Management" | Full Question: "How do you ensure successful adoption post-implementation? Describe your training programs, change management methodology, and knowledge transfer approach." | Category: General | Priority: Nice to Have | Status: Open. 5. Title: "Analytics & Reporting" | Full Question: "Describe your data analytics capabilities, including AI/ML integration, dashboard options, and how you handle data governance and compliance for reporting workflows." | Category: Technical | Priority: Must Answer | Status: Open.]

[wait]

[new-chat]

Confirm 5 RFP questions are visible with Status: Open and Draft Response column empty.

[pause]

[section: demo]

[navigate: ${LIST}]

Sales gets an RFP. Five questions. Answering each one normally means digging
through old proposals, copying pieces, rewriting for the new client. Hours of
work. Watch what happens when we turn institutional knowledge into a skill.

[pause]

[open-chat]

[prompt: Create a skill called "Draft RFP Response" that takes an RFP question from this list, searches our Proposal Archive library for relevant past proposals, and drafts a response. The response should pull specific facts, metrics, and capabilities from the source documents. In the output, list which documents were used as sources. Write the response in a professional proposal tone, not a casual summary.]

[wait]

Skill created. Let's start with a question that has strong source material.

[pause]

[prompt: Draft a response to the Cloud Migration Approach question]

[wait]

Look at what it produced. A professional 2-3 paragraph response, specific
numbers from real past proposals — the 12-16 week timeline, the Woodgrove Bank
reference, the 6-phase methodology. And at the bottom: Sources. It's not
generating from thin air. It's pulling from your actual archive.

[pause]

Let's try one that has to pull from multiple documents at once.

[prompt: Draft a response to the Data Security Standards question]

[wait]

This one drew from the Northwind security doc and the Fabrikam analytics doc —
two different proposals, synthesized into one coherent answer. Zero-trust
architecture, AES-256 encryption, SOC 2 Type II. Real specifics, real citations.

[pause]

Now let's do all the Must Answer questions at once.

[prompt: Draft responses for all the Must Answer questions and save the drafts to each item]

[wait]

Three questions drafted. Draft Response column populated. Sources Used filled
in. Status updated to Drafted. That used to take half a day. We just did it in
under a minute.

[pause]

Now I want to add a trust layer. The team needs to know when the AI is
confident and when something needs human review.

[prompt: Update my Draft RFP Response skill to also include a Confidence score — High if the answer is well-supported by multiple source documents, Medium if it draws from only one source or the source is a partial match, and Low if the skill couldn't find strong supporting content and had to generalize. Save the confidence score to the Confidence column. For any Low confidence response, add a note at the top: "Needs human review — limited source material found."]

[wait]

[prompt: Re-draft all the open RFP questions with the updated skill]

[wait]

Same quality responses — but now each one has a confidence score. Most are
High or Medium because we have strong source material. If a question didn't
have backing in the archive, it would show Low and flag itself for review.

That's the trust layer. The skill searches your knowledge, cites its sources,
and tells you when it's not sure. That's how you put AI into a real workflow.

[pause]

[screenshot: tools/screenshots/15-skills-rfp-response-final.png]

[section: reset]

[navigate: ${SITE}]

[open-chat]

[new-chat]

